          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        <date>Sunday Sunday 10 Nov. 1833</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Dear <addressee>Leeser</addressee></p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)"><persName>Mr. Moses E. Levy</persName> (of
                                                  <placeName>Florida</placeName>) intending to<lb/>
                                        leave here in the morning I steal a few moments from
                                        dinner<lb/> to address you—as otherwise I should not have
                                        time to do so<lb/> as I have as yet not had the opportunity
                                        of conferring with<lb/> my Brother on business matters, to
                                        which purpose I must<lb/> devote my afternoon possibly
                                        evening also–</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">We had a tedious time on <date>Friday</date>—only
                                        reached <placeName>Birden<lb/>=town</placeName> at 1 oclock
                                        owing to the fog in the
                                        <placeName>Delaware</placeName>—and<lb/> waited there till
                                        3, so as to allow the cars from <placeName>NYork</placeName>
                                        to<lb/> arrive before we should start. In consequence of all
                                        which<lb/> we only arrived at the wharf at 8 o'clock at
                                        night and<lb/> after, I may say contending for our baggage,
                                        was at last<lb/> pursuing my route up our brilliant lively
                                                  <placeName>Broadway</placeName><lb/> Thank God
                                        found all well, and somewhat uneasy at the<lb/> delay. Your
                                        letters to Cousin <persName>Isaac</persName> I delivered
                                        him, and<lb/> that for <persName>Mr. Hart</persName>, handed
                                        to his nephew <persName>Mr. Davids</persName> to convey<lb/>
                                        to him.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">We this day were favored with delightful
                                        weather<lb/> and altho' not a very full, a very liberal
                                        audience to<lb/> listen to the Discourse of <persName>Dr.
                                                  Peixotto</persName>, at our temporary
                                        syna<lb/>-gogue, we collected about $270 which really is a
                                        most opportune event for our society. Please mention to
                                        ma<lb/> chere amie <persName>Miss R.</persName> this
                                        fortunate circumstance. <sic>to</sic> wit the<lb/> delivery
                                        of the discourse, as I pride myself (perhaps rather</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>presumptuously) on her sympathy in my behalf-having<lb/> been
                                        acquainted with the repeated disappointment, I have<lb/> (in
                                        common with a few others) endured on this account–<lb/>
                                        Since I am thus <hi rend="underline">fairly</hi> embarked on
                                        a subject, than which<lb/> a more pleasing one could not
                                        offer itself, say also that<lb/> to the <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >letter</hi> and in the very spirit of the
                                        commands with<lb/> which I was both honored entrusted by
                                        her—have<lb/> I fulfilled them. I delivered within a brief
                                        hour after<lb/> my arrival her large letter to
                                                  <persName>Miss Hortensia[?]</persName>, and
                                                  <persName>Miss<lb/> Pesoa</persName>—and I pleased
                                        myself <hi rend="underline">doubly</hi> last evening in<lb/>
                                        conveying the small packet intended <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >solely</hi> for the use of<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr. Robert P Noah</persName> c—and in spending a
                                        few very agreeable <del>few</del><lb/> hours with the major,
                                        his wife sister. They made many enqui<lb/>=ries, to which I
                                        responded as well as circumstances enabled<lb/> me. Now my
                                        dear friend, for the life and soul of me I cannot<lb/>
                                        separate or detach from my mind the image of her, whom
                                        I<lb/> so recently left in
                                        <placeName>Philad</placeName>:–Prepare yourself if you
                                        have<lb/> courage or patience, sympathy or indulgence, to
                                        read the outpour<lb/>=ings of a doating passion. Yes if I
                                        must allow myself<lb/> vanquished, by the blandishments of a
                                        cultivated mind, an<lb/> amiable disposition, and a model of
                                        domestic virtues, for so do<lb/> I esteem the idol to which
                                        my heart (you may say impiously<lb/> or insanely)
                                                  <sic>yeilds</sic> its homage then must you be
                                        content to find<lb/> my letters filled with such expressions
                                        as my feelings dictate.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>I had just composed myself yesterday to address those thoughts<lb/>
                                        which the place and occasion required. I should devote
                                        impi<lb/>=ous supplication. When the language of the
                                        [Hebrew] presented to<lb/> my mind the whole detail of
                                                  <persName>Isaacs</persName> marriage with
                                                  <persName>Rebekah</persName></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Perhaps the name alone first <sic>rivetted</sic>
                                        my attention, be it as it<lb/> may. down went my prayer
                                        book, and I <sic>dont</sic> think I ever<lb/> perused this
                                        interesting narrative with stronger feelings of
                                        admiration<lb/> at the amiability and benevolence of
                                                  <persName>Rebekah</persName>. it is true my
                                        ideas<lb/> of gallantry could not approve the acquiescence
                                        of the servant<lb/> suffering her to draw water for the
                                        camels and I hope yo[?]<lb/> find in our traditions
                                        sufficient grounds to prove, that her [?]<lb/> nature was
                                        not imposed on to that extent. What a [?]<lb/> subject for a
                                        discourse! Just by way of a bit of peandal[?], small<lb/> I
                                        ask if one of our southern Belles would do the like for a
                                        husband<lb/> even were she to know the reward before
                                        hand—which the kind <persName>Rebe=<lb/>kah</persName> did
                                        not. When you have nought better to write you can touch<lb/>
                                        on this subject.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">When you see <persName>Mrs. R Hart</persName>,
                                        please tell her I delivered her<lb/> message to
                                                  <persName>Miss Hendricks</persName>. I hope
                                                  <persName>Mr. A</persName> has recovered, and
                                        that<lb/> his family may enjoy better health, and enabled to
                                        visit us soon.</p>
                              <p>Remember me with much esteem to all enquiring friends, and<lb/> to
                                        those whom I more particularly care for, and admire,
                                        you<lb/> may strengthen that expression. all which I leave
                                        to your judgt..<lb/> of me and him or her, as the case may
                                        be.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The family desires as usual to be remembered to
                                        you and<lb/> as ever believe me your friend <persName
                                                  role="author">Theodore</persName>.</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Walnut, 2d. Door west of 4th Street</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName>Mr. M. E Levy</persName>
                                        <hi rend="indent(2)">
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                                        </hi>
                              </p>
                              <p><hi rend="underline">Forget not</hi>, when you write to speak on
                                        that subject, the most pleasing, that<lb/> my mind can dwell
                                        on– and of one which, every thing will be interesting–</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">
                                        <persName role="author">T.</persName>
                              </p>
